# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: american-national-standards-institute
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] A **501(c)(3) organization** is a United States corporation, trust, unincorporated association, or other type of organization exempt from federal income tax under section 501(c)(3) of Title 26 of the United States Code.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] It is one of the 29 types of 501(c) nonprofit organizations in the U.S.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] The 501(c)(3) exemption applies also for any non-incorporated community chest, fund, cooperating association or foundation organized and operated exclusively for those purposes.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] There are also supporting organizations—often referred to in shorthand form as *Friends of* organizations.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] 26 U.S.C. § 170 provides a deduction for federal income tax purposes, for some donors who make charitable contributions to most types of 501(c)(3) organizations, among others.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] Regulations specify which such deductions must be verifiable to be allowed (e.g., receipts for donations of $250 or more).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] The basic requirement of obtaining tax-exempt status is that the organization is specifically limited in powers to purposes that the IRS classifies as tax-exempt purposes.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] This limiting of the powers is crucial to obtaining tax exempt status with the IRS and then on the state level.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] Organizations acquire 501(c)(3) tax exemption by filing IRS Form 1023.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] As of 2006, the form must be accompanied by an $850 filing fee if the yearly gross receipts for the organization are expected to average $10,000 or more.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] If yearly gross receipts are expected to average less than $10,000, the filing fee is reduced to $400.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] The IRS released a software tool called Cyber Assistant in 2013, which was succeeded by Form 1023-EZ in 2014.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] There is an alternative way for an organization to obtain status if an organization has applied for a determination and either there is an actual controversy regarding a determination or the Internal Revenue Service has failed to make a determination.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] Prior to December 30, 1969, nonprofit organizations could declare themselves to be tax-exempt under Section 501(c)(3) without first obtaining Internal Revenue Service recognition by filing Form 1023 and receiving a determination letter.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] A nonprofit organization that did so prior to that date could still be subject to challenge of its status by the Internal Revenue Service.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] An individual may not take a tax deduction on gifts made to a 501(c)(3) organization that is organized and operated exclusively for the testing for public safety.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] In the case of tuition fees paid to a private 501(c)(3) school or a church school, the payments are not tax-deductible charitable contributions because they are payments for services rendered to the payee or the payee's children.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] The payments are not tax-deductible charitable contributions even if a significant portion of a church school's curriculum is religious education.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] For a payment to be a tax-deductible charitable contribution, it must be a voluntary transfer of money or other property with no expectation of procuring financial benefit equal to the transfer amount.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] Before donating to a 501(c)(3) organization, a donor can consult the searchable online IRS list of charitable organizations to verify that the organization qualifies to receive tax-deductible charitable contributions.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] Consumers may file IRS Form 13909, with documentation, to complain about inappropriate or fraudulent (i.e., fundraising, political campaigning, lobbying) activities by any 501(c)(3) organization.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] Most 501(c)(3) must disclose the names and addresses of certain large donors to the Internal Revenue Service on their annual returns, but this information is not required to be made available to the public, unless the organization is an independent foundation.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] Churches are generally exempt from this reporting requirement.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] Every 501(c)(3) organization must make available for public inspection its application for tax-exemption, including its Form 1023 or Form 1023-EZ and any attachments, supporting documents, and follow-up correspondence with the Internal Revenue Service.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] Annual returns must be publicly available for a three-year period beginning with the due date of the return, including any extension of time for filing.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] The Internal Revenue Service provides information about specific 501(c)(3) organizations through its Tax Exempt Organization Search online.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] A private nonprofit organization, GuideStar, provides information on 501(c)(3) organizations.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] ProPublica's Nonprofit Explorer provides copies of each organization's Form 990 and, for some organizations, audited financial statements.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] WikiCharities, is a nonprofit database of nonprofits and charities by name, location, and topic, that allows each organization to report its financials, leadership, contacts, and other activities.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] However, Open990 was a searchable database of information about organizations that had to shut down due to IRS delays in posting information online.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] Section 501(c)(3) organizations are prohibited from supporting political candidates, as a result of the Johnson Amendment enacted in 1954.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] Section 501(c)(3) organizations are subject to limits on lobbying, having a choice between two sets of rules establishing an upper bound for their lobbying activities.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] Section 501(c)(3) organizations risk loss of their tax-exempt status if these rules are violated.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] An organization that loses its 501(c)(3) status due to being engaged in political activities cannot subsequently qualify for 501(c)(3) status.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] As a result, it is common for 501(c)(3) organizations to have affiliated nonprofits that are classified as 501(c)(4) organizations, allowing the affiliate to engage in political activity without threatening 501(c)(3) status.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] Churches must meet specific requirements to obtain and maintain tax-exempt status; these are outlined in "IRS Publication 1828: Tax Guide for Churches and Religious Organizations".
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] This guide outlines activities allowed and not allowed by churches under the 501(c)(3) designation.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] Schools for the preparation of its ministers.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] Having an established congregation served by an organized ministry is of central importance.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] Points 4, 6, 8, 11, 12, and 13 are also especially important.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] Nevertheless, the 14-point list is a guideline; it is not intended to be all-encompassing, and other facts and circumstances may be relevant factors.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] Although there is no definitive definition of a church for Internal Revenue Code purposes, in 1986 the United States Tax Court said that "A church is a coherent group of individuals and families that join together to accomplish the religious purposes of mutually held beliefs.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] The United States Tax Court has stated that, while a church can certainly broadcast its religious services by radio, radio broadcasts themselves do not constitute a congregation unless there is a group of people physically attending those religious services.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] A church can conduct worship services in various specific locations rather than in one official location.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] A church may have a significant number of people associate themselves with the church on a regular basis, even if the church does not have a traditional established list of individual members.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] In order to qualify as a tax-exempt church, church activities must be a significant part of the organization's operations.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] An organization whose operations include a substantial nonexempt commercial purposes, such as operating restaurants and grocery stores in a manner consistent with a particular religion's religious beliefs does not qualify as a tax-exempt church.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] In practice, hospital policies often don't cover outside contracted physicians or narrowly defined medically necessary services, leaving patients who technically qualify for charity care still responsible for significant medical bills.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] Organizations described in section 501(c)(3) are prohibited from conducting political campaign activities to intervene in elections to public office.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] Since section 501(c)(3)'s political-activity prohibition was enacted, "commentators and litigants have challenged the provision on numerous constitutional grounds", such as freedom of speech, vagueness, and equal protection and selective prosecution.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] Historically, Supreme Court decisions, such as *Regan v.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] Taxation with Representation of Washington*, suggested that the Court, if it were to squarely examine the political-activity prohibition of § 501(c)(3), would uphold it against a constitutional challenge.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] However, some have suggested that a successful challenge to the political activities prohibition of Section 501(c)(3) might be more plausible in light of *Citizens United v.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] In contrast to the prohibition on political campaign interventions by all section 501(c)(3) organizations, public charities (but not private foundations) may conduct a limited amount of lobbying to influence legislation.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] Although the law states that "no substantial part" of a public charity's activities can go to lobbying, charities with large budgets may lawfully expend a million dollars (under the "expenditure" test) or more (under the "substantial part" test) per year on lobbying.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] The Internal Revenue Service has never defined the term "substantial part" with respect to lobbying.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] To establish a safe harbor for the "substantial part" test, the United States Congress enacted §501(h), called the Conable election after its author, Representative Barber Conable.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] The section establishes limits based on operating budget that a charity can use to determine if it meets the substantial test.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] This changes the prohibition against direct intervention in partisan contests only for lobbying.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] The organization is now presumed in compliance with the substantiality test if they work within the limits.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] The Conable election requires a charity to file a declaration with the IRS and file a functional distribution of funds spreadsheet with their Form 990.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] IRS form 5768 is required to make the Conable election.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] A 501(c)(3) organization is allowed to conduct some or all of its charitable activities outside the United States.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] A 501(c)(3) organization is allowed to award grants to foreign charitable organizations if the grants are intended for charitable purposes and the grant funds are subject to the 501(c)(3) organization's control.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] Additional procedures are required of 501(c)(3) organizations that are private foundations.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] Donors' contributions to a 501(c)(3) organization are tax-deductible only if the contribution is for the use of the 501(c)(3) organization, and that the 501(c)(3) organization is not merely serving as an agent or conduit of a foreign charitable organization.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] The 501(c)(3) organization's management should review the grant application from the foreign organization, decide whether to award the grant based on the intended use of the funds, and require continuous oversight based on the use of funds.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] If the donor imposes a restriction or earmark that the contribution must be used for foreign activities, then the contribution is deemed to be for the foreign organization rather than the 501(c)(3) organization, and the contribution is not tax-deductible.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] The purpose of the grant to the foreign organization cannot include endorsing or opposing political candidates for elected office in any country.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/501-c-3-organization] If a 501(c)(3) organization sets up and controls a foreign subsidiary to facilitate charitable work in a foreign country, then donors' contributions to the 501(c)(3) organization are tax-deductible even if intended to fund the foreign charitable activities.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] The **American National Standards Institute** (**ANSI**) is a private nonprofit organization that oversees the development of voluntary consensus standards for products, services, processes, systems, and personnel in the United States.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] The organization also coordinates U.S. standards with international standards so that American products can be used worldwide.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI accredits standards that are developed by representatives of other standards organizations, government agencies, consumer groups, companies, and others.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] These standards ensure that the characteristics and performance of products are consistent, that people use the same definitions and terms, and that products are tested the same way.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI also accredits standards developing organizations (SDOs) and provides a searchable directory of accredited standards developers (ASDs).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI similarly accredits organizations that carry out product or personnel certification in accordance with requirements defined in international standards.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] The organization's headquarters are in Washington, D.C.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI's operations office is located in New York City.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] The ANSI annual operating budget is funded by the sale of publications, membership dues and fees, accreditation services, fee-based programs, and international standards programs.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] Many ANSI regulations are incorporated by reference into United States federal statutes (i.e. by OSHA regulations referring to individual ANSI specifications).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI does not make these standards publicly available, and charges money for access to these documents; it further claims that it is copyright infringement for them to be provided to the public by others free of charge.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] These assertions have been the subject of criticism and litigation.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI was most likely formed in 1918, when five engineering societies and three government agencies founded the **American Engineering Standards Committee** (**AESC**).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] In 1928, the AESC became the **American Standards Association** (**ASA**).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] In 1966, the ASA was reorganized and became the **United States of America Standards Institute** (**USASI**).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] In February 1969, Ralph Nader harshly criticized the USASI in public remarks as "manifestly deceptive" in several different ways.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] He specifically attacked the name USASI as improperly implying some kind of official connection with the federal government of the United States.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] had been members of the United Engineering Society (UES).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] At the behest of the AIEE, they invited the U.S. government Departments of War, Navy (combined in 1947 to become the Department of Defense or DOD) and Commerce to join in founding a national standards organization.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] According to Adam Stanton, the first permanent secretary and head of staff in 1919, AESC started as an ambitious program and little else.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] Staff for the first year consisted of one executive, Clifford B.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] LePage, who was on loan from a founding member, ASME.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] An annual budget of $7,500 was provided by the founding bodies.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] In 1931, the organization (renamed ASA in 1928) became affiliated with the U.S.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] National Committee of the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), which had been formed in 1904 to develop electrical and electronics standards.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI's members are government agencies, organizations, academic and international bodies, and individuals.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] In total, the Institute represents the interests of more than 270,000 companies and organizations and 30 million professionals worldwide.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI's market-driven, decentralized approach has been criticized in comparison with more planned and organized international approaches to standardization.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] Although ANSI itself does not develop standards, the Institute oversees the development and use of standards by accrediting the procedures of standards developing organizations.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI accreditation signifies that the procedures used by standards developing organizations meet the institute's requirements for openness, balance, consensus, and due process.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI also designates specific standards as American National Standards, or ANS, when the Institute determines that the standards were developed in an environment that is equitable, accessible and responsive to the requirements of various stakeholders.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] Voluntary consensus standards quicken the market acceptance of products while making clear how to improve the safety of those products for the protection of consumers.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] There are approximately 9,500 American National Standards that carry the ANSI designation.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] The institute is the official U.S. representative to the two major international standards organizations, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), as a founding member, and the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), via the U.S.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI participates in almost the entire technical program of both the ISO and the IEC, and administers many key committees and subgroups.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] In many instances, U.S. standards are taken forward to ISO and IEC, through ANSI or the USNC, where they are adopted in whole or in part as international standards.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] Adoption of ISO and IEC standards as American standards increased from 0.2% in 1986 to 15.5% in May 2012.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] Each of the panels works to identify, coordinate, and harmonize voluntary standards relevant to these areas.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] In 2009, ANSI and the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) formed the Nuclear Energy Standards Coordination Collaborative (NESCC).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/american-national-standards-institute] NESCC is a joint initiative to identify and respond to the current need for standards in the nuclear industry.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-asc-x12] The **Accredited Standards Committee** (**ASC**) **X12** is a standards organization.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-asc-x12] Chartered by the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) in 1979, it develops and maintains the X12 Electronic data interchange (EDI) and Context Inspired Component Architecture (CICA) standards along with XML schemas which drive business processes globally.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-asc-x12] The membership of ASC X12 includes technologists and business process experts, encompassing health care, insurance, transportation, finance, government, supply chain and other industries.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-asc-x12] ASC X12 has sponsored more than 300 X12 EDI transaction sets and a growing collection of X12 XML schemas for health care, insurance, government, transportation, finance, and many other industries.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-asc-x12] ASC X12's membership includes 3,000 standards experts representing over 600 companies from multiple business domains.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-asc-x12] The ASC X12 Board of Directors (Board) and the ASC X12 Steering Committee (Steering) collaborate to ensure the best interests of ASC X12 are served.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-asc-x12] Each group has specific responsibilities and the groups cooperatively handle items or issues that span the responsibilities of both groups.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-asc-x12] ASC X12 is organized into subcommittees that develop and maintain standards for a particular set of business functions.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-asc-x12] X12F is responsible for the development and maintenance of components of the ASC X12 Standards related to the financial services industry's business activities.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-asc-x12] ASC X12F also develops and maintains interpretations, technical reports and guidelines related to its areas of responsibility.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-asc-x12] X12I is responsible for the development and maintenance of components of the ASC X12 Standards related to the transportation industry's business activities, including air, marine, rail, and motor freight transportation and Customs, logistics and multi-modal activities.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-asc-x12] ASC X12I also develops and maintains interpretations, technical reports and guidelines related to its areas of responsibility.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-asc-x12] Maintains the directory, dictionary and design rules for all the X12 standards.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-asc-x12] Also manages the process for requests for standards changes.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-asc-x12] X12M is responsible for the development and maintenance of components of the ASC X12 Standards related to the supply chain industry's business activities, excluding transportation and finance, from sourcing to delivery.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-asc-x12] There are informal industry groups created to identify issues and activities in specific areas.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-asc-x9] The **Accredited Standards Committee X9** (ASC X9, Inc.) is an ANSI (American National Standards Institute) accredited standards developing organization, responsible for developing voluntary open consensus standards for the financial services industry in the U.S.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-asc-x9] Membership in ASC X9 is open to all U.S. domiciled companies and organizations in the financial services industry.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-asc-x9] The committee was founded in 1974 under the American National Standards Institute, to develop financial industry standards following a surge in electronic banking, automated clearing, and data security needs.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-asc-x9] In 1984 it played a major role role in supporting the Check Clearing for the 21st Century Act (Check 21) through development of check image exchange and related standards.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-asc-x9] In the 1990s it expanded its cryptography standards, developing foundational specifications for secure data exchange and public key infrastructures (e.g., X9.42, X9.73, X9.24).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-asc-x9] In 2001, the organization was incorporated as ASC X9, Inc., transitioning from a pure ANSI committee to a non-profit industry consortium still accredited by ANSI.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-asc-x9] During the 2000s and 2010s it joined with international bodies like ISO/TC 68, helping shape ISO 20022 and other global standards for payments and securities messaging.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-asc-x9] The Accredited Standards Committee X9 develops, establishes, maintains, and promotes standards for the Financial Services Industry in the United States in order to facilitate delivery of financial services and products.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-c] The first standard for C was published by ANSI.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-c] Although this document was subsequently adopted by ISO/IEC and subsequent revisions published by ISO/IEC have been adopted by ANSI, "ANSI C" is still used to refer to the standard.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-c] While some software developers use the term ISO C, others are standards-body neutral and use Standard C.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-c] Informal specification in 1978 (Brian Kernighan and Dennis Ritchie book *The C Programming Language*).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-c] In 1983, the American National Standards Institute formed a committee, X3J11, to establish a standard specification of C.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-c] In 1985, the first Standard Draft was released, sometimes referred to as *C85*.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-c] In 1986, another Draft Standard was released, sometimes referred to as *C86*.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-c] The prerelease Standard C was published in 1988, and sometimes referred to as *C88*.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-c] The ANSI standard was completed in 1989 and ratified as ANSI X3.159-1989 "Programming Language C." This version of the language is often referred to as "ANSI C".
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-c] Later on sometimes the label "C89" is used to distinguish it from C90 but using the same labeling method.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-c] The same standard as C89 was ratified by ISO/IEC as ISO/IEC 9899:1990, with only formatting changes, which is sometimes referred to as C90.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-c] Therefore, the terms "C89" and "C90" refer to a language that is virtually identical.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-c] This standard has been withdrawn by both ANSI/INCITS and ISO/IEC.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-c] In 1995, the ISO/IEC published an extension, called Amendment 1, for the C standard.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-c] This was both the first standard with a __STDC_VERSION__ value (199409L) and the first version in which the year in that value did not match the year of publication (1995), leading to common names of both *C94* and *C95*.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-c] This would happen again in C17 (2018) and C23 (2024), but they are more commonly known by their earlier years, while this standard is often referred to by its later year.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-c] In March 2000, ANSI adopted the ISO/IEC 9899:1999 standard.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-c] This standard is commonly referred to as C99.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-c] This standard has been withdrawn by both ANSI/INCITS and ISO/IEC in favour of C11.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-c] C11 was officially ratified and published on December 8, 2011.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-c] Notable features include improved Unicode support, type-generic expressions using the new `_Generic` keyword, a cross-platform multi-threading API (`threads.h`), and atomic types support in both core language and the library (`stdatomic.h`).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-c] Rather than introducing new language features, it only addresses defects in C11.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-c] C23 was published in October 2024, and is the current standard for the C programming language.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-c] C2Y is an informal name for the next revision of the C programming language that is hoped to be released in the later 2020s.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-c] More technical specifications are in development and pending approval, including the fifth and final part of TS 18661, a software transactional memory specification, and parallel library extensions.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-c] ANSI C is supported by almost all the widely used compilers.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-c] GCC and Clang are two major C compilers popular today, both based on the C11 with updates including changes from later specifications such as C17.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-c] Any source code written *only* in standard C and without any hardware dependent assumptions is virtually guaranteed to compile correctly on any platform with a conforming C implementation.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-c] To mitigate the differences between K&R C and the ANSI C standard, the `__STDC__` ("standard c") macro can be used to split code into ANSI and K&R sections.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-c] In the above example, a prototype is used in a function declaration for ANSI compliant implementations, while an obsolescent non-prototype declaration is used otherwise.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-c] Those are still ANSI-compliant as of C99.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ansi-c] Note how this code checks both definition and evaluation: this is because some implementations may set `__STDC__` to zero to indicate non-ANSI compliance.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The term *speed* comes from the early days of photography.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Photographic emulsions that were more sensitive to light needed less time to generate an acceptable image and thus a complete exposure could be finished faster, with the subjects having to hold still for a shorter length of time.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Emulsions that were less sensitive were deemed "slower" as the time to complete an exposure was much longer and often usable only for still life photography.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Exposure times for photographic emulsions shortened from hours to fractions of a second by the late 19th century.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] In both film and digital photography, choice of speed will almost always affect image quality.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Higher sensitivities, which require shorter exposures, typically result in reduced image quality due to coarser film grain or increased digital image noise.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Lower sensitivities, which require longer exposures, will retain more viable image data due to finer grain or less noise, and therefore more detail.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Ultimately, sensitivity is limited by the quantum efficiency of the film or sensor.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] To determine the exposure time needed for a given film, a light meter is typically used.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Five criteria for the rating of emulsion speed have been used since the late 19th century, listed here by name and date, these criteria are: threshold (1880), inertia (1890), fixed density (1934), minimum useful gradient (1939) and fractional gradient (1939).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The threshold criterion is the point on the characteristic curve corresponding to just perceptible density above fog.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The inertia speed point of an emulsion is determined on the Hurter and Driffield characteristic curve by the intercept between the gradient of the straight line part of the curve and the line representing the base + fog (B+F) on the density axis.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The fixed density speed point is determined by defining a fixed minimum density as the basis of the emulsion speed (e.g.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The minimum useful gradient criterion places the speed point where the gradient first reaches an agreed value (e.g. tan 𝜃 = 0.2).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The fractional gradient is defined as the speed point at which the slope of the characteristic curve first reaches a fixed fraction (e.g.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] 0.3) of the average gradient over a range (e.g.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The speed of the emulsion was then expressed in 'degrees' Warnerke (sometimes seen as Warn. or °W.) corresponding with the last number visible on the exposed plate after development and fixation.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Each number represented an increase of 1/3 in speed, typical plate speeds were between 10° and 25° Warnerke at the time.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] His system saw some success but proved to be unreliable due to its spectral sensitivity to light, the fading intensity of the light emitted by the phosphorescent tablet after its excitation as well as high built-tolerances.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The concept, however, was later built upon in 1900 by Henry Chapman Jones (1855–1932) in the development of his plate tester and modified speed system.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Another early practical system for measuring the sensitivity of an emulsion was that of Hurter and Driffield (H&D), originally described in 1890, by the Swiss-born Ferdinand Hurter (1844–1898) and British Vero Charles Driffield (1848–1915).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] In their system, speed numbers were inversely proportional to the exposure required.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] For example, an emulsion rated at 250 H&D would require ten times the exposure of an emulsion rated at 2500 H&D.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The methods to determine the sensitivity were later modified in 1925 (in regard to the light source used) and in 1928 (regarding light source, developer and proportional factor)—this later variant was sometimes called "H&D 10".
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The H&D system was officially accepted as a standard in the former Soviet Union from 1928 until September 1951, when it was superseded by GOST 2817–50.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The *Scheinergrade* (Sch.) system was devised by the German astronomer Julius Scheiner (1858–1913) in 1894 originally as a method of comparing the speeds of plates used for astronomical photography.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Scheiner's system rated the speed of a plate by the least exposure to produce a visible darkening upon development.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Speed was expressed in degrees Scheiner, originally ranging from 1° to 20° Sch., with each increment of a degree corresponding to a *multiplicative* factor of increased light sensitivity.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] This multiplicative factor was determined by the constraint that an increment of 19° Sch.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] (from 1° to 20° Sch.) corresponded to a hundredfold increase in sensitivity.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Thus emulsions that differed by 1° Sch. on the Scheiner scale were ${\sqrt[{19}]{100}}=1.2742...$ -fold more (or, less) sensitive to each other.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Scheiner's system was eventually abandoned in Germany, when the standardized DIN system was introduced in 1934.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] In various forms, it continued to be in widespread use in other countries for some time.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The DIN system, officially DIN standard 4512 by the **Deutsches Institut für Normung** (then known as the **Deutscher Normenausschuß** (DNA)), was published in January 1934.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] International Congress of Photography (German: **Internationaler Kongreß für wissenschaftliche und angewandte Photographie**) held in Dresden from 3 to 8 August 1931.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The DIN system was inspired by Scheiner's system, but the sensitivities were represented as the base 10 logarithm of the sensitivity multiplied by 10, similar to decibels.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] As in the Scheiner system, speeds were expressed in 'degrees'.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Originally the sensitivity was written as a fraction with 'tenths' (for example "18/10° DIN"), where the resultant value 1.8 represented the relative base 10 logarithm of the speed.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] 'Tenths' were later abandoned with DIN 4512:1957-11, and the example above would be written as "18° DIN".
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The degree symbol was finally dropped with DIN 4512:1961-10.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Originally only meant for black-and-white negative film, the system was later extended and regrouped into nine parts, including DIN 4512-1:1971-04 for black-and-white negative film, DIN 4512-4:1977-06 for color reversal film and DIN 4512-5:1977-10 for color negative film.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] On an international level the German DIN 4512 system has been effectively superseded in the 1980s by ISO 6:1974, ISO 2240:1982, and ISO 5800:1979 where the same sensitivity is written in linear and logarithmic form as "ISO 100/21°" (now again with degree symbol).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] These ISO standards were subsequently adopted by DIN as well.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] When BS 935:1941 was published during World War II, specifying exposure tables for negative materials, it employed the same fixed-density speed criterion used in the German DIN 4512:1934 system.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The British Standard also used *logarithmic* speed numbers, following the example of Scheiner and DIN.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] When the American ASA Z38.2.1:1943 standard was published, it used a fractional gradient speed criterion and *arithmetic* speed numbers, for compatibility with Weston and GE.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] British standard BS 1380:1947 adopted the *fractional gradient* criterion of the American 1943 standard, and also included *arithmetic* speed numbers in addition to *logarithmic* numbers.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The *logarithmic* speed number proposed in the later BS 1380:1957 standard was almost identical to the DIN 4512:1957 standard, except that the BS number was +9 degrees greater than the corresponding DIN number; in 1971, the BS and DIN standards changed this to +10 degrees.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Following an increasing effort to produce international standards, the British, American, and German standards became identical in ISO 6:1974, which corresponded to BS 1380:Part1:1973.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The meter and film rating system were invented by William Nelson Goodwin, Jr., who worked for them and later received a Howard N.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Potts Medal for his contributions to engineering.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The company tested and frequently published speed ratings for most films of the time.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Weston film speed ratings could since be found on most Weston exposure meters and were sometimes referred to by film manufacturers and third parties in their exposure guidelines.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Since manufacturers were sometimes creative about film speeds, the company went as far as to warn users about unauthorized uses of their film ratings in their "Weston film ratings" booklets.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The Weston Cadet (model 852 introduced in 1949), Direct Reading (model 853 introduced in 1954) and Master III (models 737 and S141.3 introduced in 1956) were the first in their line of exposure meters to switch and utilize the meanwhile established ASA scale instead.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Other models used the original Weston scale up until ca.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Vice versa, "old" Weston film speed ratings could be converted into "new" Westons and the ASA scale by adding the same amount, that is, a film rating of 100 Weston (up to 1955) corresponded with 125 ASA (as per ASA PH2.5-1954 and before).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] This conversion was not necessary on Weston meters manufactured and Weston film ratings published since 1956 due to their inherent use of the ASA system; however, the changes of the ASA PH2.5-1960 revision may be taken into account when comparing with newer ASA or ISO values.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Prior to the establishment of the ASA scale and similar to Weston film speed ratings another manufacturer of photo-electric exposure meters, General Electric, developed its own rating system of so-called *General Electric film values* (often abbreviated as *G-E* or *GE*) around 1937.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Film speed values for use with their meters were published in regularly updated *General Electric Film Values* leaflets and in the *General Electric Photo Data Book*.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] General Electric switched to use the ASA scale in 1946.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Meters manufactured since February 1946 are equipped with the ASA scale (labeled "Exposure Index") already.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] For some of the older meters with scales in "Film Speed" or "Film Value" (e.g. models DW-48, DW-49 as well as early DW-58 and GW-68 variants), replaceable hoods with ASA scales were available from the manufacturer.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The company continued to publish recommended film values after that date, however, they were then aligned to the ASA scale.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Originally, ASA values were frequently referred to as *American standard speed numbers* or *ASA exposure-index numbers*.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The ASA scale is a linear scale, that is, a film denoted as having a film speed of 200 ASA is twice as fast as a film with 100 ASA.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The ASA standard underwent a major revision in 1960 with ASA PH2.5-1960, when the method to determine film speed was refined and previously applied safety factors against under-exposure were abandoned, effectively doubling the nominal speed of many black-and-white negative films.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] For example, an Ilford HP3 that had been rated at 200 ASA before 1960 was labeled 400 ASA afterwards without any change to the emulsion.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Similar changes were applied to the DIN system with DIN 4512:1961-10 and the BS system with BS 1380:1963 in the following years.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] In addition to the established arithmetic speed scale, ASA PH2.5-1960 also introduced logarithmic ASA grades (100 ASA = 5° ASA), where a difference of 1° ASA represented a full exposure stop and therefore the doubling of a film speed.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] For some while, ASA grades were also printed on film boxes, and they saw life in the form of the APEX speed value *Sv* (without degree symbol) as well.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] ASA PH2.5-1960 was revised as ANSI PH2.5-1979, without the logarithmic speeds, and later replaced by NAPM IT2.5–1986 of the National Association of Photographic Manufacturers, which represented the US adoption of the international standard ISO 6.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The latest issue of ANSI/NAPM IT2.5 was published in 1993.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The standard for color negative film was introduced as ASA PH2.27-1965 and saw a string of revisions in 1971, 1976, 1979, and 1981, before it finally became ANSI IT2.27–1988 prior to its withdrawal.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Color reversal film speeds were defined in ANSI PH2.21-1983, which was revised in 1989 before it became ANSI/NAPM IT2.21 in 1994, the US adoption of the ISO 2240 standard.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] On an international level, the ASA system was superseded by the ISO film speed system between 1982 and 1987, however, the arithmetic ASA speed scale continued to live on as the linear speed value of the ISO system.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] GOST (Cyrillic: ГОСТ) was an arithmetic film speed scale defined in GOST 2817-45 and GOST 2817–50.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] It was used in the former Soviet Union from October 1951, replacing Hurter & Driffield (H&D, Cyrillic: ХиД) numbers, which had been used since 1928.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] GOST 2817-50 was similar to the ASA standard, having been based on a speed point at a density 0.2 above base plus fog, as opposed to the ASA's 0.1.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] GOST markings are only found on pre-1987 photographic equipment (film, cameras, lightmeters, etc.) of Soviet Union manufacture.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] This evolved into multiple parts including GOST 10691.6–88 and GOST 10691.5–88, which both became functional on 1 January 1991.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The ASA and DIN film speed standards have been combined into the ISO standards since 1974.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The current International Standard for measuring the speed of color negative film is ISO 5800:2001 (first published in 1979, revised in November 1987) from the International Organization for Standardization (ISO).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Related standards ISO 6:1993 (first published in 1974) and ISO 2240:2003 (first published in July 1982, revised in September 1994 and corrected in October 2003) define scales for speeds of black-and-white negative film and color reversal film, respectively.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The determination of ISO speeds with digital still-cameras is described in ISO 12232:2019 (first published in August 1998, revised in April 2006, corrected in October 2006 and again revised in February 2019).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The ISO system defines both an arithmetic and a logarithmic scale.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The arithmetic ISO scale corresponds to the arithmetic ASA system, where a doubling of film sensitivity is represented by a doubling of the numerical film speed value.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] In the logarithmic ISO scale, which corresponds to the DIN scale, adding 3° to the numerical value constitutes a doubling of sensitivity.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] For example, a film rated ISO 200/24° is twice as sensitive as one rated ISO 100/21°.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Commonly, the logarithmic speed is omitted; for example, "ISO 100" denotes "ISO 100/21°", while logarithmic ISO speeds are written as "ISO 21°" as per the standard.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] and rounding to the nearest integer; the log is base 10.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] and rounding to the nearest standard arithmetic speed in Table 1 below.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] APEX *Sv* values 1 to 10 correspond with logarithmic ASA grades 1° to 10° found in ASA PH2.5-1960.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] ASA arithmetic speeds from 4 to 5 are taken from ANSI PH2.21-1979 (Table 1, p.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] ASA arithmetic speeds from 6 to 3200 are taken from ANSI PH2.5-1979 (Table 1, p.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] ISO arithmetic speeds from 4 to 3200 are taken from ISO 5800:1987 (Table "ISO speed scales", p.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] ISO arithmetic speeds from 6 to 10000 are taken from ISO 12232:1998 (Table 1, p.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] ISO 12232:1998 does not specify speeds greater than 10000.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] However, the upper limit for *S*noise 10000 was given as 12500, suggesting that ISO may have envisioned a progression of 12500, 25000, 50000, and 100000, similar to that from 1250 to 10000.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] This was consistent with ASA PH2.12-1961.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] For digital cameras, Nikon, Canon, Sony, Pentax, and Fujifilm chose to express the greater speeds in an exact power-of-2 progression from the highest previously realized speed (6400) rather than rounding to an extension of the existing progression.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Speed ratings greater than 10000 have finally been defined in ISO 12232:2019.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Most of the modern 35 mm film SLRs support an automatic film speed range from ISO 25/15° to 5000/38° with DX-coded films, or ISO 6/9° to 6400/39° manually (without utilizing exposure compensation).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The film speed range with support for TTL flash is smaller, typically ISO 12/12° to 3200/36° or less.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The Booster accessory for the Canon Pellix QL (1965) and Canon FT QL (1966) supported film speeds from 25 to 12800 ASA.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The film speed dial of the Canon A-1 (1978) supported a speed range from 6 to 12800 ASA (but already called ISO film speeds in the manual).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] On this camera exposure compensation and extreme film speeds were mutually exclusive.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The Leica R8 (1996) and R9 (2002) officially supported film speeds of 8000/40°, 10000/41° and 12800/42° (in the case of the R8) or 12500/42° (in the case of the R9), and utilizing its ±3 EV exposure compensation the range could be extended from ISO 0.8/0° to ISO 100000/51° in half exposure steps.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] As discussed in the ASA and DIN sections, the definition of the ASA and DIN scales changed several times in the 1950s up into the early 1960s making it necessary to convert between the different scales.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Since the ISO system combines the newer ASA and DIN definitions, this conversion is also necessary when comparing older ASA and DIN scales with the ISO scale.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The picture shows an ASA/DIN conversion in a 1952 photography book in which 21/10° DIN was converted to ASA 80 instead of ASA 100.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Some classic camera's exposure guides show the old conversion as they were valid at the time of production, for example the exposure guide of the classic camera Tessina (since 1957), where 21/10° DIN is related to ASA 80, 18° DIN to ASA 40, etc.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Users of classic cameras may become confused if they are not aware of the historic background of changing standards.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Film speed is found from a plot of optical density vs. log of exposure for the film, known as the *D*–log *H* curve or Hurter–Driffield curve.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] There typically are five regions in the curve: the base + fog, the toe, the linear region, the shoulder, and the overexposed region.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The exposure *H*m, in lux-s, is that for point m when the specified contrast condition is satisfied.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] This value is then rounded to the nearest standard speed in Table 1 of ISO 6:1993.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Determining speed for color negative film is similar in concept but more complex because it involves separate curves for blue, green, and red.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The film is processed according to the film manufacturer's recommendations rather than to a specified contrast.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] ISO speed for color reversal film is determined from the middle rather than the threshold of the curve; it again involves separate curves for blue, green, and red, and the film is processed according to the film manufacturer's recommendations.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Film speed is used in the exposure equations to find the appropriate exposure parameters.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Four variables are available to the photographer to obtain the desired effect: lighting, film speed, f-number (aperture size), and shutter speed (exposure time).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The equation may be expressed as ratios, or, by taking the logarithm (base 2) of both sides, by addition, using the APEX system, in which every increment of 1 is a doubling of exposure; this increment is commonly known as a "stop".
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The effective f-number is proportional to the ratio between the lens focal length and aperture diameter, the diameter itself being proportional to the square root of the aperture area.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Thus, a lens set to f/1.4 allows twice as much light to strike the focal plane as a lens set to f/2.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Therefore, each f-number factor of the square root of two (approximately 1.4) is also a stop, so lenses are typically marked in that progression: f/1.4, 2, 2.8, 4, 5.6, 8, 11, 16, 22, 32, etc..
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The ISO arithmetic speed has a useful property for photographers without the equipment for taking a metered light reading.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Correct exposure will usually be achieved for a frontlighted scene in bright sun if the aperture of the lens is set to f/16 and the shutter speed is the reciprocal of the ISO film speed (e.g.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Exposure index, or EI, refers to speed rating assigned to a particular film and shooting situation in variance to the film's actual speed.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] It is used to compensate for equipment calibration inaccuracies or process variables, or to achieve certain effects.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The exposure index may simply be called the *speed setting*, as compared to the speed *rating*.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] For example, a photographer may rate an ISO 400 film at EI 800 and then use push processing to obtain printable negatives in low-light conditions.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Another example occurs where a camera's shutter is miscalibrated and consistently overexposes or underexposes the film; similarly, a light meter may be inaccurate.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] One may adjust the EI setting accordingly in order to compensate for these defects and consistently produce correctly exposed negatives.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Upon exposure, the amount of light energy that reaches the film determines the effect upon the emulsion.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] If the brightness of the light is multiplied by a factor and the exposure of the film decreased by the same factor by varying the camera's shutter speed and aperture, so that the energy received is the same, the film will be developed to the same density.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The systems for determining the sensitivity for an emulsion are possible because reciprocity holds over a wide range of customary conditions.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] In practice, reciprocity works reasonably well for normal photographic films for the range of exposures between 1/1000 second to 1/2 second.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] However, this relationship breaks down outside these limits, a phenomenon known as reciprocity failure.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The size of silver halide grains in the emulsion affects film sensitivity, which is related to granularity because larger grains give film greater sensitivity to light.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Fine-grain film, such as film designed for portraiture or copying original camera negatives, is relatively insensitive, or "slow", because it requires brighter light or a longer exposure than a "fast" film.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Fast films, used for photographing in low light or capturing high-speed motion, produce comparatively grainy images.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Kodak has defined a "Print Grain Index" (PGI) to characterize film grain (color negative films only), based on perceptual just-noticeable difference of graininess in prints.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] They also define "granularity", a measurement of grain using an RMS measurement of density fluctuations in uniformly exposed film, measured with a microdensitometer with 48 micrometre aperture.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Granularity varies with exposure — underexposed film looks grainier than overexposed film.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Some high-speed black-and-white films, such as Ilford Delta 3200 and P3200 T-Max are marketed with film speeds in excess of their true ISO speed as determined using the ISO testing method.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] According to the respective data sheets, the Ilford product is actually an ISO 1000 film, while the Kodak film's speed is nominally 800 to 1000 ISO.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The manufacturers do not indicate that the 3200 number is an ISO rating on their packaging.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Kodak and Fuji also marketed E6 films designed for pushing (hence the "P" prefix), such as Ektachrome P800/1600 and Fujichrome P1600, both with a base speed of ISO 400.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The DX codes on the film cartridges indicate the marketed film speed (i.e.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] 3200), not the ISO speed, in order to automate shooting and development.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] In digital camera systems, an arbitrary relationship between exposure and sensor data values can be achieved by setting the signal gain of the sensor.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The relationship between the sensor data values and the lightness of the finished image is also arbitrary, depending on the parameters chosen for the interpretation of the sensor data into an image color space such as sRGB.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The usual design is that the camera's parameters for interpreting the sensor data values into sRGB values are fixed, and a number of different EI choices are accommodated by varying the sensor's signal gain in the analog realm, prior to conversion to digital.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Some camera designs provide at least some EI choices by adjusting the sensor's signal gain in the digital realm ("expanded ISO").
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Digital cameras have far surpassed film in terms of sensitivity to light, with ISO equivalent speeds of up to 4,560,000, a number that is unfathomable in the realm of conventional film photography.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The ISO standard ISO 12232:2006 gave digital still camera manufacturers a choice of five different techniques for determining the exposure index rating at each sensitivity setting provided by a particular camera model.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Three of the techniques in ISO 12232:2006 were carried over from the 1998 version of the standard, while two new techniques allowing for measurement of JPEG output files were introduced from CIPA DC-004.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Depending on the technique selected, the exposure index rating could depend on the sensor sensitivity, the sensor noise, and the appearance of the resulting image.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The standard specified the measurement of light sensitivity of the entire digital camera system and not of individual components such as digital sensors, although Kodak has reported using a variation to characterize the sensitivity of two of their sensors in 2001.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The *Recommended Exposure Index* (REI) technique, new in the 2006 version of the standard, allows the manufacturer to specify a camera model's EI choices arbitrarily.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The choices are based solely on the manufacturer's opinion of what EI values produce well-exposed sRGB images at the various sensor sensitivity settings.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] This is the only technique available under the standard for output formats that are not in the sRGB color space.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] This is also the only technique available under the standard when multi-zone metering (also called *pattern* metering) is used.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Because the output level is measured in the sRGB output from the camera, it is only applicable to sRGB images—typically JPEG—and not to output files in raw image format.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] It is not applicable when multi-zone metering is used.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The CIPA DC-004 standard requires that Japanese manufacturers of digital still cameras use either the REI or SOS techniques, and DC-008 updates the Exif specification to differentiate between these values.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Consequently, the three EI techniques carried over from ISO 12232:1998 are not widely used in recent camera models (approximately 2007 and later).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] As those earlier techniques did not allow for measurement from images produced with lossy compression, they cannot be used at all on cameras that produce images only in JPEG format.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The *saturation-based* (SAT or Ssat) technique is closely related to the SOS technique, with the sRGB output level being measured at 100% white rather than 18% gray.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The SOS value is effectively 0.704 times the saturation-based value.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Because the output level is measured in the sRGB output from the camera, it is only applicable to sRGB images—typically TIFF—and not to output files in raw image format.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The two *noise-based* techniques have rarely been used for consumer digital still cameras.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] These techniques specify the highest EI that can be used while still providing either an "excellent" picture or a "usable" picture depending on the technique chosen.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] An update to this standard has been published as ISO 12232:2019, defining a wider range of ISO speeds.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] ISO speed ratings of a digital camera are based on the properties of the sensor and the image processing done in the camera, and are expressed in terms of the luminous exposure *H* (in lux seconds) arriving at the sensor.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] is a factor depending on the transmittance *T* of the lens, the vignetting factor *v*(*θ*), and the angle *θ* relative to the axis of the lens.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] where $H_{\mathrm {sat} }$ is the maximum possible exposure that does not lead to a clipped or bloomed camera output.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Typically, the lower limit of the saturation speed is determined by the sensor itself, but with the gain of the amplifier between the sensor and the analog-to-digital converter, the saturation speed can be increased.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The factor 78 is chosen such that exposure settings based on a standard light meter and an 18-percent reflective surface will result in an image with a grey level of 18%/√2 = 12.7% of saturation.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The factor √2 indicates that there is half a stop of headroom to deal with specular reflections that would appear brighter than a 100% reflecting diffuse white surface.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The *noise-based speed* is defined as the exposure that will lead to a given signal-to-noise ratio on individual pixels.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Two ratios are used, the 40:1 ("excellent image quality") and the 10:1 ("acceptable image quality") ratio.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] These ratios have been subjectively determined based on a resolution of 70 pixels per cm (178 DPI) when viewed at 25 cm (9.8 inch) distance.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The noise is defined as the standard deviation of a weighted average of the luminance and color of individual pixels.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The noise-based speed is mostly determined by the properties of the sensor and somewhat affected by the noise in the electronic gain and AD converter.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] In addition to the above speed ratings, the standard also defines the *standard output sensitivity* (SOS), how the exposure is related to the digital pixel values in the output image.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] where $H_{\mathrm {sos} }$ is the exposure that will lead to values of 118 in 8-bit pixels, which is 18 percent of the saturation value in images encoded as sRGB or with gamma = 2.2.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The standard specifies how speed ratings should be reported by the camera.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] If the noise-based speed (40:1) is *higher* than the saturation-based speed, the noise-based speed should be reported, rounded *downwards* to a standard value (e.g.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The rationale is that exposure according to the lower saturation-based speed would not result in a visibly better image.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] In addition, an exposure latitude can be specified, ranging from the saturation-based speed to the 10:1 noise-based speed.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] If the noise-based speed (40:1) is *lower* than the saturation-based speed, or undefined because of high noise, the saturation-based speed is specified, rounded upwards to a standard value, because using the noise-based speed would lead to overexposed images.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The camera may also report the SOS-based speed (explicitly as being an SOS speed), rounded to the nearest standard speed rating.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] The SOS rating could be user controlled.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] In all cases, the camera should indicate for the white balance setting for which the speed rating applies, such as daylight or tungsten (incandescent light).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Despite these detailed standard definitions, cameras typically do not clearly indicate whether the user "ISO" setting refers to the noise-based speed, saturation-based speed, or the specified output sensitivity, or even some made-up number for marketing purposes.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Because the 1998 version of ISO 12232 did not permit measurement of camera output that had lossy compression, it was not possible to correctly apply any of those measurements to cameras that did not produce sRGB files in an uncompressed format such as TIFF.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] Following the publication of CIPA DC-004 in 2006, Japanese manufacturers of digital still cameras are required to specify whether a sensitivity rating is REI or SOS.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] A greater SOS setting for a given sensor comes with some loss of image quality, just like with analog film.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] However, this loss is visible as image noise rather than grain.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/asa-film-speed] APS- and 35 mm-sized digital image sensors, both CMOS and CCD based, do not produce significant noise until about *ISO 1600*.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] ASCII encodes each code-point as a value from 0 to 127 – storable as a seven-bit integer.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Ninety-five code-points are printable, including digits *0* to *9*, lowercase letters *a* to *z*, uppercase letters *A* to *Z*, and commonly used punctuation symbols.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] For example, the letter `i` is represented as 105 (decimal).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Also, ASCII specifies 33 non-printing control codes which originated with Teletype devices, most of which are now obsolete.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The control characters that are still commonly used include carriage return, line feed, and tab.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] ASCII lacks code-points for characters with diacritical marks and therefore does not directly support terms or names such as résumé, jalapeño, or René.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] But, depending on hardware and software support, some diacritical marks can be rendered by overwriting a letter with a backtick (`) or tilde (~).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA) prefers the name **US-ASCII** for this character encoding.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] ASCII is the standardisation of a seven-bit teleprinter code developed in part from earlier telegraph codes.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Work on the ASCII standard began in May 1961, when IBM engineer Bob Bemer submitted a proposal to the American Standards Association's (ASA) (now the American National Standards Institute or ANSI) X3.2 subcommittee.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The first edition of the standard was published in 1963, contemporaneously with the introduction of the Teletype Model 33.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] It later underwent a major revision in 1967, and several further revisions until 1986.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] In contrast to earlier telegraph codes such as Baudot, ASCII was ordered for more convenient collation (especially alphabetical sorting of lists), and added controls for devices other than teleprinters.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] ASCII was developed under the auspices of a committee of the American Standards Association (ASA), called the X3 committee, by its X3.2 (later X3L2) subcommittee, and later by that subcommittee's X3.2.4 working group (now INCITS).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The ASA later became the United States of America Standards Institute (USASI) and ultimately became the American National Standards Institute (ANSI).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] With the other special characters and control codes filled in, ASCII was published as ASA X3.4-1963, leaving 28 code positions without any assigned meaning, reserved for future standardization, and one unassigned control code.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] There was some debate at the time whether there should be more control characters rather than the lowercase alphabet.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The indecision did not last long: during May 1963 the CCITT Working Party on the New Telegraph Alphabet proposed to assign lowercase characters to *sticks* 6 and 7, and International Organization for Standardization TC 97 SC 2 voted during October to incorporate the change into its draft standard.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The X3.2.4 task group voted its approval for the change to ASCII at its May 1963 meeting.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Locating the lowercase letters in *sticks* 6 and 7 caused the characters to differ in bit pattern from the upper case by a single bit, which simplified case-insensitive character matching and the construction of keyboards and printers.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] It added the brace and vertical bar characters.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] It renamed some control characters – SOM became SOH.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] It moved or removed others – RU was removed.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The use of ASCII format for Network Interchange was described in 1969.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] That document was formally elevated to an Internet Standard in 2015.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] In the X3.15 standard, the X3 committee also addressed how ASCII should be transmitted (least significant bit first) and recorded on perforated tape.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] They proposed a 9-track standard for magnetic tape and attempted to deal with some punched card formats.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The X3.2 subcommittee designed ASCII based on the earlier teleprinter encoding systems.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Like other character encodings, ASCII specifies a correspondence between digital bit patterns and character symbols (i.e. graphemes and control characters).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] This allows digital devices to communicate with each other and to process, store, and communicate character-oriented information such as written language.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Before ASCII was developed, the encodings in use included 26 alphabetic characters, 10 numerical digits, and from 11 to 25 special graphic symbols.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] To include all these, and control characters compatible with the Comité Consultatif International Téléphonique et Télégraphique (CCITT) International Telegraph Alphabet No.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] 2 (ITA2) standard of 1932, FIELDATA (1956), and early EBCDIC (1963), more than 64 codes were required for ASCII.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] ITA2 was in turn based on Baudot code, the 5-bit telegraph code Émile Baudot invented in 1870 and patented in 1874.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The committee debated the possibility of a shift function (like in ITA2), which would allow more than 64 codes to be represented by a six-bit code.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] In a shifted code, some character codes determine choices between options for the following character codes.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] It allows compact encoding, but is less reliable for data transmission, as an error in transmitting the shift code typically makes a long part of the transmission unreadable.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The standards committee decided against shifting, and so ASCII required at least a seven-bit code.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The committee considered an eight-bit code, since eight bits (octets) would allow two four-bit patterns to efficiently encode two digits with binary-coded decimal.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] However, it would require all data transmission to send eight bits when seven could suffice.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The committee voted to use a seven-bit code to minimize costs associated with data transmission.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Since perforated tape at the time could record eight bits in one position, it also allowed for a parity bit for error checking if desired.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Eight-bit machines (with octets as the native data type) that did not use parity checking typically set the eighth bit to 0.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The code itself was patterned so that most control codes were together and all graphic codes were together, for ease of identification.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The first two so-called *ASCII sticks* (32 positions) were reserved for control characters.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The "space" character had to come before graphics to make sorting easier, so it became position 20hex; for the same reason, many special signs commonly used as separators were placed before digits.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The committee decided it was important to support uppercase 64-character alphabets, and chose to pattern ASCII so it could be reduced easily to a usable 64-character set of graphic codes, as was done in the DEC SIXBIT code (1963).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Lowercase letters were therefore not interleaved with uppercase.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] To keep options available for lowercase letters and other graphics, the special and numeric codes were arranged before the letters, and the letter *A* was placed in position 41hex to match the draft of the corresponding British standard.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The digits 0–9 are prefixed with 011, but the remaining 4 bits correspond to their respective values in binary, making conversion with binary-coded decimal straightforward (for example, 5 is encoded to 011*0101*, where 5 is *0101* in binary).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Many of the non-alphanumeric characters were positioned to correspond to their shifted position on typewriters; an important subtlety is that these were based on *mechanical* typewriters, not *electric* typewriters.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Mechanical typewriters followed the *de facto* standard set by the Remington No.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] 2 (1878), the first typewriter with a shift key, and the shifted values of `23456789-` were `"#$%_&'()` – early typewriters omitted *0* and *1*, using *O* (capital letter *o*) and *l* (lowercase letter *L*) instead, but `1!` and `0)` pairs became standard once 0 and 1 became common.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Thus, in ASCII `!"#$%` were placed in the second stick, positions 1–5, corresponding to the digits 1–5 in the adjacent stick.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The parentheses could not correspond to *9* and *0*, however, because the place corresponding to *0* was taken by the space character.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] This was accommodated by removing `_` (underscore) from *6* and shifting the remaining characters, which corresponded to many European typewriters that placed the parentheses with *8* and *9*.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] This discrepancy from typewriters led to bit-paired keyboards, notably the Teletype Model 33, which used the left-shifted layout corresponding to ASCII, differently from traditional mechanical typewriters.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] 2, and the `,< .>` pairs were used on some keyboards (others, including the No.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] 2, did not shift `,` (comma) or `.` (full stop) so they could be used in uppercase without unshifting).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] However, ASCII split the `;:` pair (dating to No.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] 2), and rearranged mathematical symbols (varied conventions, commonly `-* =+`) to `:* ;+ -=`.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Some then-common typewriter characters were not included, notably `½ ¼ ¢`, while ^ ` ~ were included as diacritics for international use, and `< >` for mathematical use, together with the simple line characters `\ |` (in addition to common `/`).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The *@* symbol was not used in continental Europe and the committee expected it would be replaced by an accented *À* in the French variation, so the *@* was placed in position 40hex, right before the letter A.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The control codes felt essential for data transmission were the start of message (SOM), end of address (EOA), end of message (EOM), end of transmission (EOT), "who are you?" (WRU), "are you?" (RU), a reserved device control (DC0), synchronous idle (SYNC), and acknowledge (ACK).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] These were positioned to maximize the Hamming distance between their bit patterns.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] ASCII-code order is also called *ASCIIbetical* order.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Collation of data is sometimes done in this order rather than "standard" alphabetical order (collating sequence).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] An intermediate order converts uppercase letters to lowercase before comparing ASCII values.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] ASCII reserves the first 32 code points (numbers 0–31 decimal) and the last one (number 127 decimal) for control characters.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] These are codes intended to control peripheral devices (such as printers), or to provide meta-information about data streams, such as those stored on magnetic tape.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Despite their name, these code points do not represent printable characters (i.e. they are not characters at all, but signals).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] For debugging purposes, "placeholder" symbols (such as those given in ISO 2047 and its predecessors) are assigned to them.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] For example, character 0x0A represents the "line feed" function (which causes a printer to advance its paper), and character 8 represents "backspace".
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] RFC 2822 refers to control characters that do not include carriage return, line feed or white space as non-whitespace control characters.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Except for the control characters that prescribe elementary line-oriented formatting, ASCII does not define any mechanism for describing the structure or appearance of text within a document.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Other schemes, such as markup languages, address page and document layout and formatting.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The original ASCII standard used only short descriptive phrases for each control character.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The ambiguity this caused was sometimes intentional, such as when a character would be used slightly differently on a terminal link or in a data stream.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Probably the most influential single device affecting the interpretation of these characters was the Teletype Model 33 ASR, which was a printing terminal with an available paper tape reader/punch option.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Paper tape was a very popular medium for long-term program storage until the 1980s, less costly and in some ways less fragile than magnetic tape.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] In particular, the Teletype Model 33 machine assignments for codes 17 (control-Q, DC1, also known as XON), 19 (control-S, DC3, also known as XOFF), and 127 (delete) became *de facto* standards.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The Model 33 was also notable for taking the description of control-G (code 7, BEL, meaning audibly alert the operator) literally, as the unit contained an actual bell which it rang when it received a BEL character.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] When a Teletype 33 ASR equipped with the automatic paper tape reader received a control-S (XOFF, an abbreviation for transmit off), it caused the tape reader to stop; receiving control-Q (XON, transmit on) caused the tape reader to resume.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] This so-called flow control technique became adopted by several early computer operating systems as a "handshaking" signal warning a sender to stop transmission because of impending buffer overflow; it persists to this day in many systems as a manual output control technique.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] On some systems, control-S retains its meaning, but control-Q is replaced by a second control-S to resume output.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The 33 ASR also could be configured to employ control-R (DC2) and control-T (DC4) to start and stop the tape punch; on some units equipped with this function, the corresponding control character lettering on the keycap above the letter was TAPE and TAPE respectively.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The Teletype could not move its typehead backwards, so it did not have a key on its keyboard to send a BS (backspace).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Instead, there was a key marked RUB OUT that sent code 127 (DEL).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The purpose of this key was to erase mistakes in a manually-input paper tape: the operator had to push a button on the tape punch to back it up, then type the rubout, which punched all holes and replaced the mistake with a character that was intended to be ignored.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Teletypes were commonly used with the less-expensive computers from Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC); these systems had to use what keys were available, and thus the DEL character was assigned to erase the previous character.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Because of this, DEC video terminals (by default) sent the DEL character for the key marked "Backspace" while the separate key marked "Delete" sent an escape sequence; many other competing terminals sent a BS character for the backspace key.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The assumption that no key sent a BS character allowed Ctrl+H to be used for other purposes, such as the "help" prefix command in GNU Emacs.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Many more of the control characters have been assigned meanings quite different from their original ones.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The "escape" character (ESC, code 27), for example, was intended originally to allow sending of other control characters as literals instead of invoking their meaning, an "escape sequence".
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] This is the same meaning of "escape" encountered in URL encodings, C language strings, and other systems where certain characters have a reserved meaning.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Over time this interpretation has been co-opted and has eventually been changed.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] In modern usage, an ESC sent *to* the terminal usually indicates the start of a command sequence, which can be used to address the cursor, scroll a region, set/query various terminal properties, and more.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] They are usually in the form of a so-called "ANSI escape code" (often starting with a "Control Sequence Introducer", "CSI", "ESC [") from ECMA-48 (1972) and its successors.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Some escape sequences do not have introducers, like the "Reset to Initial State", "RIS" command "ESC c".
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] In contrast, an ESC read *from* the terminal is most often used as an out-of-band character used to terminate an operation or special mode, as in the TECO and vi text editors.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] In graphical user interface (GUI) and windowing systems, ESC generally causes an application to abort its current operation or to exit (terminate) altogether.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The reapplication of some control characters to new meanings created problems when transferring "plain text" files between systems.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The best example of this is the newline problem in various operating systems.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Teletype machines required that a line of text be terminated with a "carriage return" (to move the printhead to the beginning of the line) followed by a "line feed" (to advance the paper by one line).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The name "carriage return" comes from the fact that, on a manual typewriter, the carriage holding the paper moves while the typebars that strike the ribbon remain stationary.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The entire carriage must be pushed to the right ("returned") in order to position the paper for the next line.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] DEC operating systems (OS/8, RT-11, RSX-11, RSTS, TOPS-10, etc.) stored both characters at the end of each line in textual files, as needed by Teletype machines.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] When so-called "glass TTYs" were introduced (later called CRTs or "dumb terminals"), they followed the same logic, expecting the same CR and LF characters.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] When Gary Kildall created CP/M, he was inspired by some of the command line interface conventions used in DEC's RT-11 operating system.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Until the introduction of IBM PC DOS in 1981, IBM had no influence in this, because their 1970s operating systems used EBCDIC encoding instead of ASCII and they were oriented toward punch-card input and line printer output on which the concept of "carriage return" was meaningless.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] IBM's PC DOS (also marketed as MS-DOS by Microsoft) inherited the CRLF convention by virtue of being loosely based on CP/M, and Windows, in turn, inherited it from MS-DOS.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Placing CR and LF at the end of each line in a plain text document or data stream reflects what terminals and printers needed to receive, to display that material.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Multics introduced an innovation: it used only one character (LF), to represent the end of the line in stored files and in data streams.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Upon output, the tty driver converts the LF to CRLF, so files can be printed to a terminal without needing a command to explicitly convert the file format.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Unix and Unix-like systems adopted this design from Multics, as did Amiga systems.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] UNIX documents say "newline" or "NL" to refer to the line terminator.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Contrarily, the Radio Shack TRS-80, Apple DOS, Apple ProDOS, and classic Mac OS used a lone carriage return (CR) to terminate lines.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Apple's later operating system, Mac OS X (now called macOS) is based on Unix, so it uses line feed (LF).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] To enable communication between all these systems, the Telnet protocol defined a "Network Virtual Terminal" (NVT), wherein a single text format (ASCII with CR-LF line endings) was used for transmission and each system converted to/from its own native representation.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The File Transfer Protocol adopted the Telnet protocol, including the Network Virtual Terminal, for transmitting commands and for transferring textual files (known as "ASCII mode").
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The World Wide Web's HTTP uses a modified NVT: the standard allows lone CR and LF characters but requires that each be interpreted as an NVT CRLF.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Complexity arose in network-facing systems that didn't follow the NVT mechanism, such as some version control systems.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Bugs sometimes expose a system's native implementation to other systems on the Internet, causing data corruption.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The PDP-6 monitor, and its PDP-10 successor TOPS-10, used control-Z (SUB) as an end-of-file indication for input from a terminal.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Some operating systems such as CP/M tracked file length only in units of disk blocks, and used control-Z to mark the end of the actual text in the file.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] For these reasons, EOF, or end-of-file, was used colloquially and conventionally as a three-letter acronym for control-Z instead of SUBstitute.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The end-of-text character (ETX), also known as control-C, was inappropriate for a variety of reasons, while using control-Z as the control character to end a file is analogous to the letter Z's position at the end of the alphabet, and serves as a very convenient mnemonic aid.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] A historically common and still prevalent convention uses the ETX character convention to interrupt and halt a program via an input data stream, usually from a keyboard.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The Unix terminal driver uses the end-of-transmission character (EOT), also known as control-D, to indicate the end of a data stream.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] In the C programming language, and in Unix conventions, the null character is used to terminate text strings; such null-terminated strings can be known in abbreviation as ASCIZ or ASCIIZ, where here Z stands for "zero".
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Other representations might be used by specialist equipment, for example ISO 2047 graphics or hexadecimal numbers.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] At the time of adoption, the codes 20hex to 7Ehex would cause the printing of a visible character (a glyph), and thus were designated "printable characters".
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] These codes represent letters, digits, punctuation marks, and a few miscellaneous symbols.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] There are 95 printable characters in total.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The empty space between words, as produced by the space bar of a keyboard, is character code 20hex.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Since the space character is visible in printed text it considered a "printable character", even though it is unique in having no visible glyph.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] It is listed in the printable character table, as per the ASCII standard, instead of in the control character table.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Code 7Fhex corresponds to the non-printable "delete" (DEL) control character and is listed in the control character table.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Earlier versions of ASCII used the up arrow instead of the caret (5Ehex) and the left arrow instead of the underscore (5Fhex).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] ASCII was first used commercially during 1963 as a seven-bit teleprinter code for American Telephone & Telegraph's TWX (TeletypeWriter eXchange) network.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] TWX originally used the earlier five-bit ITA2, which was also used by the competing Telex teleprinter system.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Bob Bemer introduced features such as the escape sequence.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] His British colleague Hugh McGregor Ross helped to popularize this work – according to Bemer, "so much so that the code that was to become ASCII was first called the *Bemer–Ross Code* in Europe".
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Because of his extensive work on ASCII, Bemer has been called "the father of ASCII".
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] On March 11, 1968, US President Lyndon B.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] ASCII was the most common character encoding on the World Wide Web until December 2007, when the UTF-8 encoding surpassed it; UTF-8 is backward compatible with ASCII.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] As computer technology spread throughout the world, different standards bodies and corporations developed many variations of ASCII to facilitate the expression of non-English languages that used Roman-based alphabets.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] One could class some of these variations as "ASCII extensions", although some misuse that term to represent all variants, including those that do not preserve ASCII's character-map in the 7-bit range.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Furthermore, the ASCII extensions have also been mislabelled as ASCII.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] From early in its development, ASCII was intended to be just one of several national variants of an international character code standard.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Almost every country needed an adapted version of ASCII, since ASCII suited the needs of only the US and a few other countries.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] For example, Canada had its own version that supported French characters.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Many other countries developed variants of ASCII to include non-English letters (e.g. é, ñ, ß, Ł), currency symbols (e.g. £, ¥), etc.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] It would share most characters in common, but assign other locally useful characters to several code points reserved for "national use".
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] ISO/IEC 646, like ASCII, is a 7-bit character set.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] It does not make any additional codes available, so the same code points encoded different characters in different countries.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] C trigraphs were created to solve this problem for ANSI C, although their late introduction and inconsistent implementation in compilers limited their use.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Many programmers kept their computers on ASCII, so plain-text in Swedish, German etc.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] (for example, in e-mail or Usenet) contained "{, }" and similar variants in the middle of words, something those programmers got used to.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] For example, a Swedish programmer mailing another programmer asking if they should go for lunch, could get "N{ jag har sm|rg}sar" as the answer, which should be "Nä jag har smörgåsar" meaning "No I've got sandwiches".
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] In Japan and Korea, still as of the 2020s, a variation of ASCII is used, in which the backslash (5C hex) is rendered as ¥ (a Yen sign, in Japan) or ₩ (a Won sign, in Korea).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] This means that, for example, the file path C:\Users\Smith is shown as C:¥Users¥Smith (in Japan) or C:₩Users₩Smith (in Korea).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] In Europe, teletext character sets, which are variants of ASCII, are used for broadcast TV subtitles, defined by World System Teletext and broadcast using the DVB-TXT standard for embedding teletext into DVB transmissions.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] In the case that the subtitles were initially authored for teletext and converted, the derived subtitle formats are constrained to the same character sets.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Eventually, as 8-, 16-, and 32-bit (and later 64-bit) computers began to replace 12-, 18-, and 36-bit computers as the norm, it became common to use an 8-bit byte to store each character in memory, providing an opportunity for extended, 8-bit relatives of ASCII.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] In most cases these developed as true extensions of ASCII, leaving the original character-mapping intact, but adding additional character definitions after the first 128 (i.e., 7-bit) characters.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] ASCII itself remained a seven-bit code: the term "extended ASCII" has no official status.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] For some countries, 8-bit extensions of ASCII were developed that included support for characters used in local languages (for example, ISCII for India and VISCII for Vietnam).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Even for markets where it was not necessary to add many characters to support additional languages, manufacturers of early home computer systems often developed their own 8-bit extensions of ASCII to include additional characters, such as box-drawing characters, semigraphics, and video game sprites.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Often, these additions also replaced control characters (index 0 to 31, as well as index 127) with even more platform-specific extensions.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] In other cases, the extra bit was used for some other purpose, such as toggling inverse video; this approach was used by ATASCII, an extension of ASCII developed by Atari.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Most ASCII extensions are based on ASCII-1967 (the current standard), but some extensions are instead based on the earlier ASCII-1963.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] For example, PETSCII, which was developed by Commodore International for their 8-bit systems, is based on ASCII-1963.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Likewise, many Sharp MZ character sets are based on ASCII-1963.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] IBM defined code page 437 for the IBM PC, replacing the control characters with graphic symbols such as smiley faces, and mapping additional graphic characters to the upper 128 positions.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Digital Equipment Corporation developed the Multinational Character Set (DEC-MCS) for use in the popular VT220 terminal as one of the first extensions designed more for international languages than for block graphics.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Apple defined Mac OS Roman for the Macintosh and Adobe defined the PostScript Standard Encoding for PostScript; both sets contained "international" letters, typographic symbols and punctuation marks instead of graphics, more like modern character sets.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] The ISO/IEC 8859 standard (derived from the DEC-MCS) provided a standard that most systems copied (or at least were based on, when not copied exactly).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] A popular further extension designed by Microsoft, Windows-1252 (often mislabeled as ISO-8859-1), added the typographic punctuation marks needed for traditional text printing.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] ISO-8859-1, Windows-1252, and the original 7-bit ASCII were the most common character encoding methods on the World Wide Web until 2008, when UTF-8 overtook them.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] ISO/IEC 4873 introduced 32 additional control codes defined in the 80–9F hexadecimal range, as part of extending the 7-bit ASCII encoding to become an 8-bit system.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Unicode and the ISO/IEC 10646 Universal Character Set (UCS) have a much wider array of characters and their various encoding forms have begun to supplant ISO/IEC 8859 and ASCII rapidly in many environments.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] While ASCII is limited to 128 characters, Unicode and the UCS support more characters by separating the concepts of unique identification (using natural numbers called *code points*) and encoding (to 8-, 16-, or 32-bit binary formats, called UTF-8, UTF-16, and UTF-32, respectively).
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] ASCII was incorporated into the Unicode (1991) character set as the first 128 symbols, so the 7-bit ASCII characters have the same numeric codes in both sets.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] This allows UTF-8 to be backward compatible with 7-bit ASCII, as a UTF-8 file containing only ASCII characters is identical to an ASCII file containing the same sequence of characters.
[src:american-national-standards-institute/ascii] Even more importantly, forward compatibility is ensured as software that recognizes only 7-bit ASCII characters as special and does not alter bytes with the highest bit set (as is often done to support 8-bit ASCII extensions such as ISO-8859-1) will preserve UTF-8 data unchanged.
